{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"alias":"kooky-graft-cap","description":"## Summary\nSession logs \"bleed\" between sessions: a new agent session appends to the previous\nsession's `session_log` ticket instead of starting a fresh one, producing a single\nenormous log that combines multiple unrelated sessions.\n\n## Root cause (suspected)\nThe \"current session log\" is tracked by a **local, git-ignored pointer**,\n`.rebar/current_session_log`. `append_session_log` / `log_session` / `session-log append`\ncreate a log on first use and then append to whatever the pointer names. The pointer is\n**never scoped to the actual session/agent** and is never auto-rotated at session\nboundaries — so once written it persists across sessions, and every later session's\nappends land on the same old log ticket until someone manually runs\n`session-log start`. rebar has no session identifier of its own (see related epic\n`crust-fetch-stump`), so it cannot detect that a new session has begun.\n\n## Reproduction Steps\n1. In session A: `rebar session-log append \"work on thing A\"` (creates a log, writes the pointer).\n2. Finish session A without ever calling `session-log start`.\n3. In an unrelated session B (same checkout): `rebar session-log append \"work on thing B\"`.\n4. Inspect the log: `rebar session-logs --limit 5` / `rebar show <log-id>`.\n\n- **Expected:** session B's entry is in its own new `session_log` (or at least clearly\n  attributable to session B); logs stay per-session and reasonably sized.\n- **Actual:** session B appends to session A's log via the stale\n  `.rebar/current_session_log` pointer; the single log grows without bound and mixes\n  entries from multiple unrelated sessions, making retrieval-by-keyword noisy and the\n  bodies huge.\n\n## Impact\n- Session logs become extremely long and mix unrelated work, defeating their purpose as\n  durable, per-session, keyword-retrievable records.\n- Large combined bodies are exactly what the `session_log` type was designed to keep out\n  of the hot paths; a giant shared log undermines that intent.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A new session does not silently append to a prior session's `session_log`; the\n      first `append` in a new session writes to a fresh log (auto-rotation) or the pointer\n      is scoped so cross-session bleed cannot happen.\n- [ ] The rotation/scoping mechanism is documented (CLAUDE.md session-logs section +\n      `docs/` as appropriate) and does not require agents to remember `session-log start`.\n- [ ] Backward compatible: existing pointer/log behavior for a single continuous session\n      is unchanged; absent any session identifier the behavior degrades safely.\n- [ ] A regression test demonstrates that two distinct sessions produce distinct logs\n      (or the same log only when genuinely the same session).","id":"76e9-a6f0-3632-42ee","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"bug","title":"Session logs bleed between sessions — pointer never rotates, producing one giant multi-session log"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1783224955829936001,"uuid":"4f0979bf-8a3d-4ebb-9154-dbdb21fc24c7"}